<!-- 01 INTRO / DISAMBIGUATION -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · What we service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">A range is the freestanding or slide-in combo unit, cooktop on top, oven below.</h2>

    <p>Some people call it a stove. Some people use the words interchangeably. For repair purposes, the distinction matters: a range is one chassis, one set of controls, one warranty. We service the whole thing, both the burners on top and the oven below, on the same dispatch.</p>

    <p>If your unit is a cooktop dropped into a counter with a separate built-in wall oven, that's two different appliances and two different service pages: <a href="/services/cooktop-repair/">cooktop repair</a> and <a href="/services/wall-oven-repair/">wall oven repair</a>. If you searched "stove repair" because that's the word you grew up with, see <a href="/services/stove-repair/">stove repair</a>, the underlying service is the same scope. If you have an induction cooktop specifically (drop-in or part of a slide-in range), see <a href="/services/induction-cooktop-repair/">induction cooktop repair</a> for the induction-specific diagnostic.</p>

    <p>Our techs service ranges across LA County, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. Same-day in most cases. $89 residential diagnostic, waived with repair. No emergency surcharge. BHGS #A49573, EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410), BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 GAS / ELECTRIC / INDUCTION FRAMING -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Three architectures, three repair playbooks</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Gas, electric, induction. Pricing tier matters too.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Gas ranges (most common LA)</h3>
    <p>Natural-gas connection at the wall, surface burners on top, gas oven below. Surface igniters fire each burner; the oven uses a hot-surface igniter or pilot system depending on vintage. Most LA homes built before 2015 are gas. Failure modes concentrate at the igniters (year 4 to 7), oven temperature sensors, and gas valves on year 10+ units.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Electric ranges (rentals, smaller homes, Inland)</h3>
    <p>Coil-top ranges (Frigidaire FFEF, GE JBP, older Whirlpool) and glass-top radiant ranges (newer Samsung, LG, Whirlpool). Bake and broil elements in the oven, coil or radiant elements on the cooktop. Element burnout at year 7 to 10 is the dominant failure mode, plus oven temperature sensor drift and control board issues at year 9 to 13.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Induction ranges (rising in coastal Westside)</h3>
    <p>Magnetic-coil cooktop, separate resistive oven below. Slide-in induction is the more common form factor in LA: Bosch HEI series, Samsung NZ slide-in, GE Profile induction. Requires magnetic-bottom cookware. Repair scope splits cleanly: induction-specific failures concentrate at the generator board (the inverter that drives the coils, $780 to $1,200 replacement); oven side fails like any electric oven (bake/broil element, sensor, board).</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Pro-style ranges ($8,000 to $15,000+ tier)</h3>
    <p>Wolf DF and GR series, Viking 7 and Tuscany, Thermador Pro Grand and Professional, BlueStar Platinum and RNB, Capital Culinarian and Connoisseurian. We see these in Beverly Hills, Bel Air, Malibu, Pacific Palisades, Hidden Hills kitchens. Pro-style ranges are designed for 18 to 25 year service lives, the math almost always favors repair through year 18, sometimes longer. Different parts catalogs from mid-market mass-production lines.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Mid-market ranges ($800 to $2,500 tier)</h3>
    <p>GE Profile, Samsung NX, LG LRG, Whirlpool WFG, KitchenAid KFGG, JennAir JGRP, Maytag MGR, Frigidaire FFGF, Amana AGR. Most LA rentals and standard new builds. Year 7 to 10 is the typical replace threshold once a major repair (control board, gas valve) crosses 50% of replacement cost.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 COMMON FAILURES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Common range failures we see in LA</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Ten failure modes account for nearly every range service call.</h2>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Surface igniter failure (gas, year 4 to 7).</strong> Click but no flame on one or more burners. Per-igniter replacement $200 to $340 with labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Spark module failure (gas, year 8 to 12).</strong> No click on any burner. Single-module replacement covers all burners. $260 to $420.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas valve sticking (gas, year 10+).</strong> Burner stuck partially open or partially closed. $440 to $680 part plus labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Bake element burnout (electric, year 7 to 10).</strong> Visible burn-through or element breaks the resistance test. $200 to $360 part with labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Broil element burnout (electric).</strong> Same failure mode as bake element, less frequently used so it lasts longer. $200 to $360.</li>
      <li><strong>Oven temperature sensor drift (year 5 to 8).</strong> Sensor reports cold while element runs constantly, or vice versa. $200 to $340.</li>
      <li><strong>Convection fan motor (year 8 to 12).</strong> Motor seizes or bearings wear, fan stops or rattles. $340 to $540.</li>
      <li><strong>Control board failure (year 9 to 13 mid-market, year 12 to 16 pro-style).</strong> Display dead, error codes cascade, oven won't reach setpoint. Mid-market boards $440 to $720, pro-style Wolf/Viking/Thermador boards $680 to $1,100.</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket compression and hinge sag.</strong> Heat leaks at door, oven runs hotter than setpoint to compensate. Gasket plus hinge service $200 to $380.</li>
      <li><strong>Induction generator board (induction-specific, any age but more often year 4 to 8).</strong> Cooktop dead while oven still works. $780 to $1,200 replacement.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Recent jobs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Real repair stories from the last few weeks.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Composite examples; model numbers, ages, and prices are accurate to typical scope.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pasadena · GE Profile PGB940SEJSS gas range, 9 years old</h3>
      <p>Two surface burners not igniting, oven running hot. Diagnosed: front-left igniter failed, oven temperature sensor drifted 35°F low (oven compensating with longer element-on time). Replaced both. Total: $89 plus $260 igniter plus $260 sensor plus 1 hour = $385.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Beverly Hills · Wolf DF366 dual-fuel pro-range, 11 years old</h3>
      <p>Display intermittent, error code on oven side, no spark on right cooktop zones. Diagnosed: control board partial failure plus spark module fault. Replaced both, calibrated oven temperature post-board-replacement. Total: $89 plus $720 board plus $310 spark module plus 2 hours = $1,180. Owner did the math against $9,500 replacement Wolf DF, repair was the obvious call.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Marina del Rey · Samsung NX58H5600SS gas range, 6 years old</h3>
      <p>Oven running cold, breaker tripping intermittently. Diagnosed: bake element shorted to ground (year-6 typical for Samsung NX), oven temp sensor reading off. Replaced bake element and sensor. Total: $89 plus $215 element plus $135 sensor plus 1 hour = $440.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>West Hollywood · Bosch HEI8054U slide-in induction range, 4 years old</h3>
      <p>All four induction zones dead, oven still functional. Diagnosed: induction generator board failure (premature on a 4-year unit, but Bosch HEI generator boards have a known year 3 to 5 weak run). Replaced generator board, retested all zones with magnetic test cookware. Total: $89 plus $890 board plus 1.5 hours = $980.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Calabasas · Whirlpool WFG320M0BS gas range, 8 years old</h3>
      <p>Right-rear burner stuck partially open even with knob in off position. Diagnosed: gas valve seized at right-rear position, year-8 typical on Whirlpool WFG. Replaced gas valve, leak-tested all four positions, verified shutoff. Total: $89 plus $440 valve plus 1.5 hours = $560.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 BRAND POOL -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Brands we service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Twelve residential range brands cover most LA installs.</h2>

    <p><strong>Pro-style tier ($8,000 to $15,000+):</strong> <a href="/brands/wolf-range-repair/">Wolf</a> (DF dual-fuel and GR all-gas), <a href="/brands/viking-range-repair/">Viking</a> (7 Series, Tuscany), <a href="/brands/thermador-range-repair/">Thermador</a> (Pro Grand, Professional), plus BlueStar (Platinum and RNB) and Capital (Culinarian, Connoisseurian) which we service without dedicated brand pages.</p>

    <p><strong>Premium tier ($2,500 to $5,000):</strong> <a href="/brands/jennair-range-repair/">JennAir</a> (Whirlpool family, designer-grade), <a href="/brands/bosch-range-repair/">Bosch</a> (HEI induction, HGI gas, dual-fuel slide-in, Bosch does make freestanding ranges for the US market).</p>

    <p><strong>Mid-market tier ($800 to $2,500):</strong> <a href="/brands/ge-range-repair/">GE</a> (Profile, Café, Monogram), <a href="/brands/samsung-range-repair/">Samsung</a> (NX gas, NE electric, NZ slide-in induction), <a href="/brands/lg-range-repair/">LG</a> (LRG gas, LRE electric), <a href="/brands/whirlpool-range-repair/">Whirlpool</a> (WFG gas, WFE electric), <a href="/brands/maytag-range-repair/">Maytag</a> (MGR gas, MER electric), <a href="/brands/frigidaire-range-repair/">Frigidaire</a> (FFGF gas, FFEF coil-top, FFEH glass-top), <a href="/brands/amana-range-repair/">Amana</a> (AGR gas, AER electric, value tier of Whirlpool family).</p>

    <p>KitchenAid sells ranges on the Whirlpool platform but doesn't have a dedicated brand page yet, we service them under Whirlpool-platform diagnostic procedures.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 REPAIR VS REPLACE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">06 · Repair vs replace</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Honest framing by tier.</h2>

    <p><strong>Mid-market ($800 to $2,500 GE/Samsung/LG/Whirlpool/Maytag/Frigidaire/Amana):</strong> repair through year 8 to 10 makes sense. Beyond year 10, if a major repair (control board, gas valve, induction generator) crosses 50% of replacement cost, replace is the call. We tell you the math at diagnostic.</p>

    <p><strong>Premium ($2,500 to $5,000 Bosch/JennAir):</strong> repair through year 13 to 15. These units are built for it.</p>

    <p><strong>Pro-style ($8,000 to $15,000+ Wolf/Viking/Thermador/BlueStar/Capital):</strong> repair through year 18 to 20+. A $700 control board on a 12-year-old Wolf range is an obvious repair, not a replace conversation. Don't let anyone tell you otherwise. Pro-style ranges are designed for service life, that's what you paid the premium for.</p>
  </div>
</section>

